<subSubSection type="distribution">
<paragraph pageNumber="155">
This genus includes three palaearctic and several nearctic species immediate recognisable from other formicine ants by the long sickle shaped toothless mandible and much reduced thin palps, formula 4: 2. Members of this genus raid nests of ants the 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:29086" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica fusca Linnaeus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="155" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fusca">Formica fusca</taxonomicName>
group to carry away pupae to be reared as auxiliaries in the ho[[..]] nest. 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2509" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Polyergus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Polyergus Latreille" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="155" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Polyergus</taxonomicName>
workers are unable to feed themselves and are entirely dependent o captive 
<taxonomicName LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:2506" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Formica" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Formica Linnaeus" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="155" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Formica</taxonomicName>
for their survival.
</paragraph>
